-- Copper, Oil Rise on China Manufacturing, U.S. Economic Data; Kiwi Advances
-- B y   S h i y i n   C h e n
-- 2010-10-01T04:29:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-01/asian-stocks-copper-climb-on-chinese-manufacturing-u-s-economic-growth.html
Copper rose to the highest since 2008
and crude oil traded above $80 a barrel after Chinese and U.S.
economic data eased concern the global recovery will falter. The
Australian and New Zealand currencies strengthened.  Copper rose 0.8 percent to $8,076 a metric ton as of 1:15
p.m. in Tokyo after earlier touching $8,085 a metric ton. Crude
reached a high of $80.43 a barrel. The Australian dollar rose to
96.94 U.S. cents and New Zealand’s currency, known as the kiwi,
traded at 73.73 U.S. cents. The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  was
little changed at 126.40, set for its fifth straight weekly
rally. Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  futures  climbed 0.1 percent.  Investor sentiment improved after China’s logistics
federation said its  purchasing managers’ index  increased to 53.8
from 51.7 in August, the fastest pace in four months. U.S.
business activity unexpectedly accelerated and fewer workers
filed claims for jobless benefits, reports said yesterday, while
U.S. Treasury Secretary  Timothy F. Geithner  said he was
confident tensions over the yuan wouldn’t lead to escalating
trade sanctions or feed into a broader global currency conflict.  “Conditions are better in the U.S. and globally than how
we are perceiving them,”  James Paulsen , chief investment
strategist at Wells Capital Management, which manages $342
billion, said in a Bloomberg Television interview. “All we see
is bad when there’s been a global recovery now for a year or a
year and a half.”  Benchmark stock indexes for  Japan , Australia, South Korea
and Taiwan swung between gains and losses. Singapore’s Straits
Times Index rose 0.4 percent and the Bombay Stock Exchange’s
 Sensitive Index  rallied 1 percent. Markets are closed in China
and Hong Kong for a holiday.  Toyota, BHP  Exporters fell in Japan, led by a 1.4 percent decline in
shares of  Toyota Motor Corp. , after the yen strengthened versus
the dollar. Mining stocks gained, with  BHP Billiton Ltd. 
climbing 1.1 percent in Sydney.  Copper for three-month delivery on the London Metal
Exchange strengthened to the highest level since Aug. 1, 2008,
and was poised for a third weekly increase. Crude for November
delivery rose as much as 0.6 percent on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, extending a 5 percent gain over the past two days.  Credit-default swap indexes fell, with the Markit iTraxx
Asia index of 50 investment-grade borrowers outside Japan
declining 2 basis points to 117 points, according to prices from
Deutsche Bank AG. The indicator of corporate credit risk in
Asia, which typically falls as investor confidence improves, was
set for its lowest closing price since Sept. 17.  Euro, U.S. Dollar  The euro gained for a fourth day versus the dollar before
reports forecast to show U.S. manufacturing slowed last month
and German retail sales increased in August. The euro climbed to
$1.3657 in Tokyo from $1.3634 yesterday in New York when it
reached $1.3683, the strongest since April 12. Fon 83.49 yen
from 83.53 yesterday when it touched 83.17 yen, the weakest
level Sept. 15.  The Institute for Supply Management’s  factory index  fell to
54.5 in September from 56.3 in August, according to a Bloomberg
survey of economists before today’s data. German retail sales
rose 0.4 percent in August after a 0.1 percent drop the prior
month, according to a Bloomberg survey ahead of data today.  South Korea’s won strengthened to 1,131.95 per dollar,
heading for a fifth weekly gain, after government data showed
consumer prices rose 3.6 percent in September, the fastest pace
in 17 months. The Taiwan dollar appreciated 0.5 percent to
NT$31.16 per dollar after the central bank yesterday raised its
benchmark interest rate by 0.125 percentage point to 1.5
percent.  To contact the reporters for this story:
